S4.T1.caption: Table 1 :  Results of post-ASR error correction on CHiME-4 test set
references:
In row 111a-111e of Table 1, we report the results of the proposed alternative prompts on the CHiME-4 dataset.
We observe that the performance is better than the baseline prompt in row 00, indicating the effectiveness of the proposed alternative prompts.

In 222a-222e of Table 1, we provide one demonstration example before asking LLMs to do error correction.
See Fig. 3 for an example.
Comparing 222a-222e with 111a-111e, we observe that including one demonstration improves the performance.

In 222a-444e of Table 1, we report the results of using EvoPrompt to optimize the set of empirically-designed prompts (i.e., Prompt-#{1,…,51…51,\dots,5}).
We provide the WER of each of the five new (i.e., mutated) prompts in each iteration.
We observe that the performance gets gradually better with more iterations.
The prompt in row 555b stands out with the lowest WER of 4.884.884.88%.
This indicates the effectiveness and potential of EvoPrompt for prompt optimization.

S4.T2.caption: Table 2 :  Example of corrected errors based on an utterance drawn from CHiME-4. Best viewed in color.
references:
Table 2 provides an example of the corrected errors.
We observe that biasing LLMs towards the domain of finance helps correct errors such as "fidelity" and "gencorp", which are financial terms.

S4.T3.caption: Table 3 :  Results of post-ASR error correction using evolutionary prompts on unseen Common Voice test set of Hyporadise
references:
Table 3 and 4 report the results on the CV and WSJ test sets.
They offer valuable understandings about the ability of the model to extend its performance beyond the data it is trained on.
The best performing mutated prompt #111 from the CHiME experiement shows a deterioration in performance on both test sets, with a higher WER compared to the baseline. This implies that the mutations implemented in Prompt #1 are not beneficial for the process of generalization.
